anized into systematic sections and engage with one another, offering complementary views. All core issues in the global ethical debate are covered: donating and procuring organs, allocating and receiving organs, as well as considering alternatives. Due to its systematic structure, the volume provides an excellent orientation for researchers, students, and practitioners alike to enable a deeper understanding of some of the most controversial issues in modern medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aBody. 4aBrain Death. 4aEthics. 4aMedical Ethics. 4aMedicine. 4aOrgan Donation. 4aPhilosophy. 4aTransplantation. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aBody.  aBrain Death.  aEthics.  aMedical Ethics.  aMedicine.  aOrgan Donation.  aPhilosophy.  aTransplantation.1 aAlpınar-Şencan, Zümrüt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAve, Anne Dalle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeier, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernat, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirnbacher, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoas, Hagai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnham-Stevens, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidovitch, Nadav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDraper, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Solveig Lena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Solveig Lena, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators